metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #570
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Idem Locus #13
metadata.description:
The artist of this art piece found its inspiration not in an individual artist, but rather in the aesthetic of an entire era - the engravings from the Late Middle Ages and the early Renaissance.

"Idem Locus" (Latin for "The Same Place") was conceived as a result of delving into the engravings of the 15th and 16th centuries, contrasting the portrayed locations with their contemporary counterparts. 

Idem Locus was part of the Blind Gallery x Feral File Vistas Edition
For more information, visit https://www.blindgallery.xyz/

metadata.name: Tranquility #47
metadata.description:
Nature is like freshing water that purifies our minds. In it, we can shake off all the noise of daily life and calm down our minds, and the tranquility of nature gives us a moment of healing. this moment gives us the feeling that time has stopped, and it gives us new energy and peace.

I hope this work will give you the least sense of tranquility.

- Palette: Spring / Summer / Fall / Winter / Blue / Red

By thion, January 2024

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #175
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: pico_punk_generator_generator.p8 #479
metadata.description:
Welcome to the ultimate pico_punk generator! This interactive token is a parameter based generator that creates unique pico_punk generators. Each one will generate one pico_punk with a number of layers chosen by you during the parameter selection phase. Additionally, you can use the buttons to navigate the generative space, and create your own pico_punks via an interactive process of discovery. This is the final pico_punk generator I intend to make, with the extra capabilities added by the parameter selection process, and the final tweaks and changes I made to the appearances and effects, I think this project is now as complete as I can ever make it.

The controls:
- arrow keys: move through the generative space... each step adds one layer to the composition
- x button: take a screenshot of the generated pico_punk
- o button: clear all layers except the current one (clean slate for building a new pico_punk)

Each layer has a chance to apply one of various visual effects, which vary in how transformative (or disruptive) they are.


pico_punks began as a project to create something akin to DOS Punks, but fully generative, without any manual intervention or pre-rendered components, using only the Pico-8 Fantasy Console. You can find the first generator here: (https://objkt.com/asset/hicetnunc/439049). In this early version, the generator was interactive, but each pico_punk was totally isolated, being generated from one unique seed and one consistent process. Over time, this evolved to this final experience: one in which the "curator", the user exploring the generator, is not just choosing from an infinite number of punks, but actually the process of exploration itself is modifying the output before your eyes.

pico_punks is all about exploring themes of irreversibility, noise, pattern recognition, pareidolia, and of course identity. What began for me as something bordering on satire, has become an integral part of how I represent myself online. It is my sincere wish that with these tools you are also able to create something unique that you feel represents you, and is something that couldn't have been made without you.

Thank you so much for these last couple years of support, and here's to many more making and collecting art together :)


Notes on minting: 
- 30% of royalties go to the minter
- 10% of royalties go to previous curated pico_punk holders
- One reserve spot is generated for each curated pico_punk held, and they stack
- One extra reserve spot is for my Mom

metadata.name: The Living Book #2 Moonrise #3
metadata.description:
I have been exploring the medium of print for years. Mixing etching, silk-screening, offset, photocopy, risography, drawing and painting to design and craft experimental art books.From the day digital, which had always fascinated me, took over my publishing practice, I always liked to create bridges between these two worlds.

The Living Books is part of this series of hybrid and experimental works where paper and digital resonate.

This issue #2 is made of 64 pages that will be minted by collectors. A book will eventually be printed and the pages will follow the mint order. Each page exists in a cover version (c) and a xerox version (x).

Controls :

‚Ä¢ Click to dive into each frame.
‚Ä¢ Press C to toggle cover mode.
‚Ä¢ Press X to toggle xerox mode.
‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

The Living Book #2 Moonrise by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Geometric Motion #30
metadata.description:
Inspired by minimalist graphic designs, this work is an exploration of combinations for simple geometrical shapes. The shapes slide under others, go out of view and reappear in an ever-changing canvas.

On a grid of 4 to 7 cells we place triangles, squares, and circles of different sizes. Their color and draw order are determined by their initial row placement. They move around freely inside the canvas indefinitely, showing a quasi-infinite number of combinations.

There are 10 possible colors, with 2 that are very rare that change the blend method to "exclusion" or "difference".

Coded with p5js

Original artwork by William Watkins ¬∑ Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #117
metadata.description:
‚ÄúShapes on a Plane‚Äù explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It‚Äôs intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I‚Äôd spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i‚Äôd take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I‚Äôd have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.
